      Contagion
   =20
 =20

I  asked yesterday if there has ever been a liquidity crisis at a crypto fi=
rm. I didn=E2=80=99t really get any answers.
  [1]
=C2=A0But you could imagine how it might go:
=09A well capitalized conservatively managed crypto lender takes in deposit=
s of crypto and lends them out to other crypto trading firms, against good =
collateral.=09The firm is borrowing short to lend long: Its deposits can be=
 recalled on demand, but its loans have longer terms and can=E2=80=99t be r=
ecalled immediately.=09Everything is fine and great, the loans are performi=
ng, the collateral is good.=09A huge huge huge huge crisis of confidence hi=
ts the world of centralized crypto firms, for reasons having nothing to do =
with this good upstanding crypto lender.=09Everyone demands their deposits =
back, from this lender and from everyone else, due to the crisis of confide=
nce.=09The lender doesn=E2=80=99t have their deposits, because it has loane=
d them to good creditworthy borrowers with good collateral and can=E2=80=99=
t get them back immediately.

In this scenario, the lender is perfectly solvent =E2=80=94=C2=A0the money =
is safe and will be paid back in full, reasonably soon, leaving more than e=
nough to repay depositors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but illiquid. It is a classic norm=
al bank run.
Is that this? Man,  what do I know:

The fallout from the collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s sprawling cryp=
to empire spread Wednesday, with digital-asset brokerage Genesis and crypto=
 exchange Gemini becoming the latest pain points.=C2=A0
Genesis is suspending redemptions and new loan originations at its lending =
business after facing what it described as =E2=80=9Cabnormal withdrawal req=
uests.=E2=80=9D Gemini, founded by Cameron Winklevoss and Tyler Winklevoss,=
 subsequently announced its yield product targeting retail investors will a=
lso halt redemptions as Genesis was a key partner in the program.=C2=A0
As a counterparty to many in the sector, Genesis=E2=80=99 financial health =
has been closely watched as a gauge of the industry=E2=80=99s strength or f=
or signs of potential contagion. Some of Genesis=E2=80=99 biggest lenders i=
nclude crypto exchange Gemini, which offers a product to users to generate =
yield through Genesis, according to its website. On Wednesday, Gemini annou=
nced that it=E2=80=99s working with Genesis to help customers redeem their =
funds from the Earn product =E2=80=9Cas quickly as possible.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6
Genesis=E2=80=99s withdrawal requests exceeded current liquidity at Genesis=
 Global Capital, the lending arm, according to interim Chief Executive Offi=
cer Derar Islim. The New York-based company has hired advisers to explore a=
ll possible options, including raising new funding, and will deliver a plan=
 for its lending business next week, Islim said. Alvarez & Marsal and the l=
aw firm Cleary Gottlieb are advising Genesis.

We talked yesterday about Binance Holdings Ltd.=E2=80=99s  proposal for a s=
ort of central bank of crypto, an =E2=80=9Cindustry recovery fund=E2=80=9D =
that would =E2=80=9Chelp projects who are otherwise strong, but in a liquid=
ity crisis.=E2=80=9D The sudden collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s cry=
pto exchange FTX.com, and his associated crypto hedge fund Alameda Research=
,=C2=A0could=C2=A0trigger liquidity crises at otherwise healthy crypto firm=
s. Or, of course, not. Those firms could have had assets at FTX that are no=
w gone. Or they could have made undercollateralized loans to Alameda that a=
re now gone. What do I know. In any case the FTX collapse triggered a crisi=
s of confidence that spread to other firms, healthy or not.
One solution to this problem is that the central bank of crypto could sort =
it out: Firms that run into trouble could go to Binance, and Binance could =
examine their books and decide if they=E2=80=99re solvent, and if they are =
then the industry recovery fund could lend them the money to keep their doo=
rs open. It  seems to be moving forward:

Binance Chief Executive Changpeng Zhao said on Wednesday there was signific=
ant interest from industry players in a recovery fund his company plans to =
launch to help crypto projects facing a liquidity squeeze following the col=
lapse of rival FTX.
Speaking at a conference in Abu Dhabi, Zhao said he doesn't have an exact f=
igure in mind for the size of the recovery fund.
"There are players that have strong financials and we should band together;=
 we've got significant interest so far," he said, declining to name other e=
xchanges or institutions at this point.

But isn=E2=80=99t that a weird solution, for crypto? That some fund run by =
the biggest exchange would examine each firm=E2=80=99s secret balance sheet=
s and decide who is worthy of a bailout? What if =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what if the=
re was some sort of=C2=A0decentralized=C2=A0solution? For instance, what if=
 crypto firms made their balance sheets=C2=A0public, perhaps with some sort=
 of auditing from a neutral expert=C2=A0accountant, so that investors could=
 decide for themselves which firms were solvent and which were in trouble?
Oh I am kidding, a little. Of course my point is that this is how normal pu=
blic companies in traditional finance=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0including big ban=
ks =E2=80=94=C2=A0work. But it is not like the published audited quarterly =
balance sheets of big public=C2=A0traditional financial institutions actual=
ly tell you all=C2=A0that=C2=A0much about their financial health, in a cris=
is; they are mostly too complicated and too delayed to provide definitive a=
nswers to questions like =E2=80=9Cdid this bank run out of money an hour ag=
o?=E2=80=9D But they help. The actual method that traditional finance has h=
it upon for addressing these problems is a complex combination of (1) publi=
c financial disclosure, (2) safety-and-soundness regulation to keep banks f=
rom taking too many dumb risks, (3) capital and liquidity regulation to mak=
e sure they have enough money, (4) central bank liquidity support, (5) depo=
sit insurance for customers, etc.
Even=C2=A0before last week=E2=80=99s FTX meltdown,   I liked to say=C2=A0th=
at the crypto industry managed to reinvent the 2008 financial crisis, compl=
ete with opaque leverage and financial contagion. And for ages I have been =
saying that crypto is in the business of re-learning all the lessons of tra=
ditional finance. This week, it is learning the lesson of =E2=80=9Cit is go=
od to have a central bank.=E2=80=9D But I am not sure that=E2=80=99s the=C2=
=A0best=C2=A0lesson to learn here? And it is certainly not the=C2=A0only=C2=
=A0one.=C2=A0
 Elsewhere:

BlockFi, which said in a Monday blog post that it had =E2=80=9Csignificant =
exposure=E2=80=9D to FTX and the company=E2=80=99s related entities, is pre=
