Earlier this year a big trader on the London Metals Exchange   ran into tro=
uble. He had a huge short position in nickel futures, and the price of nick=
el went up a lot when Russia invaded Ukraine. As a result, this trader =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Xiang Guangda of Tsingshan Holding Group Co. =E2=80=94 had big =
losses, and the LME called his brokers and demanded that they post more col=
lateral against his losing positions. The brokers called him for collateral=
, and he didn=E2=80=99t have it. So the brokers liquidated his nickel posit=
ions =E2=80=94=C2=A0no, just kidding, Xiang was too big and important, so t=
he brokers did=C2=A0not=C2=A0liquidate his futures positions. Instead there=
 was   a sort of weird ad hoc scramble in which the brokers loaned him some=
 money to keep him afloat, the LME=C2=A0shut down trading for a week=C2=A0s=
o he wouldn=E2=80=99t have to liquidate, and it=C2=A0reversed some trades t=
hat had already happened=C2=A0so that he wouldn=E2=80=99t lose too much mon=
ey. Eventually, in some sense, this =E2=80=9Cworked=E2=80=9D: The price of =
nickel normalized, the LME reopened, and Xiang was able to close out his po=
sitions at a more modest loss.
People got really mad about this, for a number of reasons. For one thing it=
 seems unfair to cancel trades to bail out one big trader; it is arbitrary,=
 and the opposite of how markets are supposed to work, and particularly har=
sh for the people on the other side of the trades. Also Xiang was a well-co=
nnected Chinese metals tycoon, and the LME is Hong Kong-owned, and  there w=
ere some theories about the LME bending its rules for=C2=A0favored clients.=
 Also it just exposed a certain ricketiness in the system: Shouldn=E2=80=99=
t the LME manage risk and positions so that it=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0ha=
ve to shut down for a week because someone made a bad trade?
A bit later, FTX proposed a plan to get into the business of futures tradin=
g in the US with a novel clearing structure. We   discussed this proposal i=
n June, and here I am going to oversimplify it, but for our purposes the tw=
o key innovations were:
=09In traditional futures market structure, the exchange (like LME) takes c=
ollateral from brokers, and the brokers take collateral from their customer=
s who have positions. In FTX=E2=80=99s proposal, the exchange (FTX) would f=
ace customers directly, cutting out middlemen and holding the customers=E2=
=80=99 collateral to support their trades.=09In traditional futures market =
structure, there are some delays and fuzziness around margin calls. If your=
 position moves against you, the exchange will call your broker for more co=
llateral, and your broker will call you for more collateral. But there will=
 be some time between when the position moves against you and when you get =
called for collateral =E2=80=94=C2=A0during which things might get worse, o=
r they might recover. And if you=E2=80=99re big enough and your broker call=
s you for collateral, you can try saying things like =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D =
and it might work, as it did for Xiang. The exchanges sometimes make the ju=
dgment call that, if a trader doesn=E2=80=99t post collateral, they=E2=80=
=99ll let it go, because putting that trader in default will cause a bigger=
 crisis. =E2=80=9CWe chose to give the appropriate amount of time not to di=
slocate the market and create a bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D an executiv=
e of a traditional exchange  said about one hair-raising day in the markets=
, in discussions about FTX=E2=80=99s proposal. And: =E2=80=9CI had the keys=
 to the castle at that point in time, and it would=E2=80=99ve been a very b=
ad day.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile FTX=E2=80=99s proposal was to recalculate margin=
 requirements every 30 seconds, 24 hours a day, and if a trader=E2=80=99s m=
argin fell below the requirements, that trader would automatically and inst=
antly be liquidated, with no room for judgment or delay.=C2=A0

This, FTX implied, was how its own international crypto futures exchange al=
ready operated (outside of US regulation), and it was good. It reduced cred=
it risk and made markets fairer and more orderly. When we talked about it i=
n June, I was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0interested but equivocal. The FTX model struck=
 me as a bit more rigid and crypto-y and =E2=80=9Ccode is law=E2=80=9D than=
 you might want; sometimes you=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0miss a margin call because y=
ou=E2=80=99re asleep and that seems harsh. On the other hand, the LME exper=
ience was fresh in everyone=E2=80=99s mind, and the FTX proposal seemed lik=
e an improvement over=C2=A0that. I wrote:
There are=C2=A0debates about whether this is good or bad; simplistically, y=
ou=E2=80=99d expect the FTX model to lead to=C2=A0more=C2=A0defaults and li=
quidations, but for those defaults to be=C2=A0less bad. In the traditional =
system, sometimes people will have a =E2=80=9Ctechnical issue,=E2=80=9D and=
 the exchange will =E2=80=9Cgive the appropriate amount of time not to disl=
ocate the market and create a bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D and it will w=
ork out fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0but occasionally it=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0wor=
k out fine, and by delaying the exchange will have caused a much bigger pro=
blem.
Anyway the proposal got a lot of attention, and a lot of people and firms f=
rom traditional finance argued both sides. Loosely speaking I would say tha=
t traditional exchange operators did not like this proposal, while electron=
ic high-frequency-trader-type firms thought it was an improvement over the =
current system of exchange operators=C2=A0having a lot of discretion.
Last week FTX blew up. We are still learning the details of how it blew up,=
 but the leading explanation seems to have roughly=C2=A0these features:
=09Alameda Research, a crypto hedge fund that is affiliated with FTX (both =
founded by Sam Bankman-Fried, both run out of the same group apartment in t=
he Bahamas, etc.), had huge leveraged positions on FTX and elsewhere.=09FTX=
 loaned Alameda lots of money to keep those positions going.=09As Alameda=
=E2=80=99s problems got worse, FTX gave it more money, rather than shutting=
