  [1] I actually got one very funny answer, which is: =E2=80=9CMt. Gox?=E2=
=80=9D A rough overview of the Mt. Gox story  is: (1) Mt. Gox was the large=
st crypto exchange for a while, (2) in 2014 it got hacked and all its Bitco=
ins were stolen, (3) it went bankrupt and customers had to wait for years f=
or a recovery, (4) in the meantime it got back some but not all of its Bitc=
oins, (5) also in the meantime the price of Bitcoin soared, so (6) by the t=
ime the customers got their recovery, Mt. Gox had *way* more assets =E2=80=
=94 measured in dollars and yen =E2=80=94 then the customers had lost. So a=
t some level you could say =E2=80=9CMt. Gox had assets, it temporarily lost=
 access to them, but then it got them back and had more than enough to pay =
off all of its customers, so it was just a liquidity crisis.=E2=80=9D But n=
ot really. For one thing, the customers *didn=E2=80=99t* all get paid back,=
 measured in Bitcoin; they lost Bitcoins and got back fewer Bitcoins. (But =
those Bitcoins were worth more dollars.) For another thing, getting all you=
r assets stolen is traditionally a solvency problem, even if later you get =
some of them back.


  [2] A note on entities. That balance sheet is not the audited balance she=
et of a particular legal entity running the FTX exchange. It is not the aud=
ited balance sheet of anything, but as far as I can tell it is a spreadshee=
t of all the stuff that FTX, Alameda Research and Sam Bankman-Fried can scr=
ape together, offset by $9 billion of FTX customer liabilities. So some thi=
ngs on that balance sheet =E2=80=94 in particular a stake in Robinhood Mark=
ets Inc. =E2=80=94 seem to belong to Bankman-Fried entities that are not pa=
rt of the FTX bankruptcy, but are being thrown in here to raise cash. I am =
going to say =E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=9D in the text but I mean more like =E2=80=
=9Cthe FTX/Alameda/SBF consolidated group.=E2=80=9D One thing that I do not=
 understand is the status of FTX.us, FTX=E2=80=99s US entity, which is sepa=
rate from FTX but also seems to have shut withdrawals.


  [3] That is: $554 million of the FTT token that provides fee discounts on=
 FTX itself, $2,187 million of the SRM token of FTX=E2=80=99s Project Serum=
 decentralized exchange, and $616 million of the MAPS token of another FTX =
project. I think some other assets on that balance sheet might also fall in=
to this category, though in smaller sizes. And $982 million of Solana=E2=80=
=99s SOL token are also a risky proposition if you think that the success o=
f the Solana blockchain depends in part on its ties to FTX.


  [4] Also it is silly to be too precise here, but the balance sheet we all=
 saw =E2=80=94 because the Financial Times published it =E2=80=94 is from l=
ast Thursday. I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what time it took its prices fro=
m, but I conservatively estimate that FTT and MAPS are down about 40% since=
 then, with SRM down about 14%. That puts the value of this stash at about =
$2.56 billion, down almost $800 million from last Thursday, almost enough t=
o wipe out the net equity on that balance sheet.


  [5] That number is, like, there is about $1 billion of liquid assets on t=
he balance sheet, and about $9 billion owed to customers, so if you pay out=
 the $1 billion and get $8 billion more of cash from an investor, you can p=
ay off the customers. And then the investors who put in the $8 billion get =
to keep the $9 billion of semi-liquid and illiquid assets, making this =E2=
=80=94 on Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s math =E2=80=94 an attractive deal for tho=
se investors. That=E2=80=99s the theory.


