<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are some=C2=A0tweets that Sam Bankman-Fri=
ed=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29719674.2=
76531/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkyNzM5MzkzNTMzNzkyM=
jU4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe258b917" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted last night</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few weeks ago, FTX was handling ~$10b/day of=
 volume and billions of transfers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there was too much leverage--more than I r=
ealized. =C2=A0A run on the bank and market crash exhausted liquidity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So what can I try to do? =C2=A0Raise liquidity=
, make customers whole, and restart.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe I'll fail. Maybe I won't get anything mo=
re for customers than what's already there.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I've certainly failed before. You all know tha=
t now, all too well.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But all I can do is to try. I've failed enough=
 for the month.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And part of me thinks I might get somewhere.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I know you've all seen this, but here's where =
things stand today, roughly speaking. [LOTS OF CAVEATS, ETC.]</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Liquid: -$8b<br />Semi: +$5.5b<br />Illiquid: =
+$3.5b</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yeah, maybe that $9b illiquid M2M isn't wo=
rth $9b (+$1b net). OTOH--a month ago it was worth $18b; +$10b net.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked on Monday about the <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZn=
QuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMGMyYTU1YjYtZDM0Yy00Njg1LThhOGQtM2M5NjI4ZjFmMTg1/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB95df0e37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> rough balance sheet</a> that FTX sent a=
round to investors last week in a desperate effort to raise more capital be=
fore filing for bankruptcy on Friday.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=99s Balance S=
heet Was Bad,=E2=80=9D was my headline.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s an Excel file full of the howling of ghosts=
 and the shrieking of tortured souls,=E2=80=9D I wrote. =E2=80=9CIf you loo=
k too long at that spreadsheet, you will go insane.=E2=80=9D I will not rep=
eat too much of my reasoning here =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXM=
tYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTExNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0752167a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  go read Monday=E2=80=99s post if=
 you want</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the=C2=A0<em>main=C2=A0</em>point was that=
, of the=C2=A0$9.6 billion of assets reflected on that balance sheet at mar=
ket values last week, at least $3.3 billion was in crypto tokens (mainly FT=
T, SRM and MAPS) that were created by FTX, were held mainly by FTX, and wer=
e tied to the future value of FTX=E2=80=99s businesses.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0My guess was that the actual realizable market value of those tok=
ens is much closer to zero than it is to $3.3=C2=A0billion.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the numbers in Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s twe=
et last night =E2=80=94=C2=A0negative $8 billion of net liquid assets, but =
$5.5 billion of =E2=80=9Csemi-liquid=E2=80=9D assets and $3.5 billion of il=
liquid assets, for a net equity of positive $1 billion =E2=80=94 reflect al=
most exactly=C2=A0what=E2=80=99s on that balance sheet. The only possible c=
onclusion is that he is=C2=A0<em>shopping that same balance sheet, the one =
we all saw and gasped at, after filing for bankruptcy</em>, in the hopes of=
 raising enough money (roughly $8 billion<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>) to pay out his customers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what to say about that ex=
cept that it=E2=80=99s amazing? I want it to work, because if it does it wi=
ll be one of the most surprising and interesting financial-markets developm=
ents ever. Imagine a world where it works. Imagine that this evening Bankma=
n-Fried tweets =E2=80=9Cgood news, Investor X has agreed to put in $8 billi=
on, due diligence is complete and the check has cleared, all customer withd=
rawals will be honored immediately,=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s all true.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In that imaginary world, how could you explain=
 Investor X=E2=80=99s decision? Here are some possible scenarios:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bankman-Fried is right, and I am wron=
g, about FTX=E2=80=99s balance sheet. The stuff that he classifies as =E2=
=80=9Csemi-liquid=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cilliquid,=E2=80=9D which he marks t=
o market at $9 billion, really is worth at least $9 billion. Investor X doe=
s its due diligence on these assets and concludes that those tokens that FT=
X made up really are worth at least $3.3 billion, and it is correct, and it=
 buys FTX and makes customers whole and does well because it acquired at le=
ast $9 billion of assets for $8 billion. This scenario would, among other t=
hings, be <em>incredibly</em> bullish for crypto. The takeaway would be tha=
t tokens made up by a crypto exchange, tokens tied to the future revenue of=
 that exchange, retain their value=C2=A0<em>even when that exchange goes ba=
nkrupt after misplacing customer funds</em>. The FTT token is valuable, if =
at all, because you can use it to get discounts on trading fees at FTX, and=
 because it shares in the trading fees that FTX collects. What is the prese=
nt value of those benefits, today? If your answer is =E2=80=9Cat least half=
 a billion dollars,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s just=C2=A0<em>amazing</em>.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A variation on that scenario is somet=
hing like: FTX=E2=80=99s stash of crypto assets=C2=A0is worthless, but FTX=
=E2=80=99s <em>business</em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the exchange, the technolo=
gy, the customer goodwill, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is worth more than $8=C2=A0b=
illion, so if you buy it and make customers whole you=E2=80=99ll make a pro=
fit. Again that seems challenging,=C2=A0<em>now</em>. If you buy FTX, you=
=E2=80=99ll have to work pretty hard to keep the customers.=C2=A0</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I am right, and Bankman-Fried is wrong, abo=
ut FTX=E2=80=99s balance sheet, but Investor X is also wrong. =E2=80=9CSRM =
is the token of a decentralized crypto exchange protocol called Serum, and =
if Serum takes off then SRM holders will share in the trading fees on Serum=
, and Serum is poised to be enormously valuable, so our stash of SRM is wor=
th billions, so you should give us billions=C2=A0for it,=E2=80=9D is roughl=
y the pitch here; in this scenario that pitch is=C2=A0<em>wrong=C2=A0</em>b=
ut it=C2=A0<em>works</em>. Investor X is like =E2=80=9Cooh decentralized fi=
nance, that can=E2=80=99t miss, the market is huge, $8 billion for all of t=
hese tokens is a bargain,=E2=80=9D and just hands over the $8 billion for a=
 pile of magic beans that turn out to be worthless. And Investor X, rather =
than FTX=E2=80=99s customers, is left holding the bag. This scenario seems =
far-fetched, but in broad outlines it is=C2=A0<em>a thing that worked not s=
o long ago.</em>=C2=A0Could you get venture capitalists to put in hundreds =
of millions of dollars, at least, to back FTX and to invest in tokens with =
some vague promise of utility in a decentralized-finance future? Sure, you =
could. Can you do it<em>=C2=A0now</em>, at <em>FTX</em>, which is=C2=A0<em>=
in bankruptcy=C2=A0</em>for=C2=A0<em>very notoriously misplacing customer m=
oney</em>? I mean! No. But I can see why Bankman-Fried might try.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I am right about FTX=E2=80=99s balance shee=
t, and Investor X knows it, but Investor X doesn=E2=80=99t care. Investor X=
 figures that FTX=E2=80=99s assets are worth less than $8 billion =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0though probably more than zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0and is willing to lose =
some number of billions of dollars to achieve some other purpose. Presumabl=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0in this very hypothetical scenario =E2=80=94=C2=A0that oth=
er purpose is something like =E2=80=9Cmaintain market confidence in crypto.=
=E2=80=9D If you are a huge well-capitalized crypto mogul or business, losi=
ng a few billion dollars to stem the contagion here and prop up the crypto =
market generally might almost make sense? (If you are a huge, secretly=C2=
=A0<em>poorly </em>capitalized crypto business, doing that could also make =
