<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earlier this year a big trader on the London M=
etals Exchange <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/297=
19674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
ItMDMtMTQvbmlja2VsLWJsb3d1cC1tYWRlLWEtbG90LW9mLXRyb3VibGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExN=
jIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRt=
X3Rlcm09MjIxMTE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8=
321a053" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  ran into trouble</a>. He had a huge short position in ni=
ckel futures, and the price of nickel went up a lot when Russia invaded Ukr=
aine. As a result, this trader =E2=80=94=C2=A0Xiang Guangda of Tsingshan Ho=
lding Group Co. =E2=80=94 had big losses, and the LME called his brokers an=
d demanded that they post more collateral against his losing positions. The=
 brokers called him for collateral, and he didn=E2=80=99t have it. So the b=
rokers liquidated his nickel positions =E2=80=94=C2=A0no, just kidding, Xia=
ng was too big and important, so the brokers did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>liq=
uidate his futures positions. Instead there was <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDcvbmlja2VsLWJpZy1zaG90LWNhbGxlZC10=
aGUtc2hvdHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5dbed131" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  a sort of weird ad hoc scra=
mble</a> in which the brokers loaned him some money to keep him afloat, the=
 LME=C2=A0<em>shut down trading for a week=C2=A0</em>so he wouldn=E2=80=99t=
 have to liquidate, and it=C2=A0<em>reversed some trades that had already h=
appened=C2=A0</em>so that he wouldn=E2=80=99t lose too much money. Eventual=
ly, in some sense, this =E2=80=9Cworked=E2=80=9D: The price of nickel norma=
lized, the LME reopened, and Xiang was able to close out his positions at a=
 more modest loss.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People got really mad about this, for a number=
 of reasons. For one thing it seems unfair to cancel trades to bail out one=
 big trader; it is arbitrary, and the opposite of how markets are supposed =
to work, and particularly harsh for the people on the other side of the tra=
des. Also Xiang was a well-connected Chinese metals tycoon, and the LME is =
Hong Kong-owned, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9sb25kb24tbWV0YWwt=
ZXhjaGFuZ2UtbG1lLWNoaW5hLWludGVyZmVyZW5jZS10cmFkaW5nLW5pY2tlbC1ydXNzaWEtY2F=
uY2VsbGF0aW9uLTExNjQ4MjI2NDAz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBffcb4239" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 there were some theories</a> about the LME bending its rules for=C2=A0favo=
red clients. Also it just exposed a certain ricketiness in the system: Shou=
ldn=E2=80=99t the LME manage risk and positions so that it=C2=A0<em>doesn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>have to shut down for a week because someone made a ba=
d trade?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bit later, FTX proposed a plan to get into t=
he business of futures trading in the US with a novel clearing structure. W=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29719674.276531/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDEvY3J=
5cHRvLWNsZWFyaW5nLWFuZC1jcmVkaXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTE2JnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6551d9d9" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  discus=
sed this proposal in June</a>, and here I am going to oversimplify it, but =
for our purposes the two key innovations were:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In traditional futures market structu=
re, the exchange (like LME) takes collateral from brokers, and the brokers =
take collateral from their customers who have positions. In FTX=E2=80=99s p=
roposal, the exchange (FTX) would face customers directly, cutting out midd=
lemen and holding the customers=E2=80=99 collateral to support their trades=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In traditional futures market st=
ructure, there are some delays and fuzziness around margin calls. If your p=
osition moves against you, the exchange will call your broker for more coll=
ateral, and your broker will call you for more collateral. But there will b=
e some time between when the position moves against you and when you get ca=
lled for collateral =E2=80=94=C2=A0during which things might get worse, or =
they might recover. And if you=E2=80=99re big enough and your broker calls =
you for collateral, you can try saying things like =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D an=
d it might work, as it did for Xiang. The exchanges sometimes make the judg=
ment call that, if a trader doesn=E2=80=99t post collateral, they=E2=80=99l=
l let it go, because putting that trader in default will cause a bigger cri=
sis. =E2=80=9CWe chose to give the appropriate amount of time not to disloc=
ate the market and create a bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D an executive of=
 a traditional exchange <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMjE2ODY2ZTctY2VjY=
i00NjUwLWFlYTUtYjlkZWRjN2Q3YzdjJw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31c35ed6" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> said about one hair-raising day in the markets</a>, in discussions about=
 FTX=E2=80=99s proposal. And: =E2=80=9CI had the keys to the castle at that=
 point in time, and it would=E2=80=99ve been a very bad day.=E2=80=9D Meanw=
hile FTX=E2=80=99s proposal was to recalculate margin requirements every 30=
 seconds, 24 hours a day, and if a trader=E2=80=99s margin fell below the r=
equirements, that trader would automatically and instantly be liquidated, w=
ith no room for judgment or delay.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, FTX implied, was how its own internation=
al crypto futures exchange already operated (outside of US regulation), and=
 it was good. It reduced credit risk and made markets fairer and more order=
ly. When we talked about it in June, I was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0interested but eq=
uivocal. The FTX model struck me as a bit more rigid and crypto-y and =E2=
=80=9Ccode is law=E2=80=9D than you might want; sometimes you=E2=80=99ll=C2=
=A0miss a margin call because you=E2=80=99re asleep and that seems harsh. O=
n the other hand, the LME experience was fresh in everyone=E2=80=99s mind, =
and the FTX proposal seemed like an improvement over=C2=A0<em>that</em>. I =
wrote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are=C2=A0debates about wheth=
er this is good or bad; simplistically, you=E2=80=99d expect the FTX model =
to lead to=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>defaults and liquidations, but for those=
 defaults to be=C2=A0<em>less bad</em>. In the traditional system, sometime=
s people will have a =E2=80=9Ctechnical issue,=E2=80=9D and the exchange wi=
ll =E2=80=9Cgive the appropriate amount of time not to dislocate the market=
 and create a bigger stress on that,=E2=80=9D and it will work out fine =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but occasionally it=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>work out f=
ine, and by delaying the exchange will have caused a much bigger problem.</=
p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the proposal got a lot of attention, an=
d a lot of people and firms from traditional finance argued both sides. Loo=
sely speaking I would say that traditional exchange operators did not like =
this proposal, while electronic high-frequency-trader-type firms thought it=
 was an improvement over the current system of exchange operators=C2=A0havi=
ng a lot of discretion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week FTX blew up. We are still learning t=
he details of how it blew up, but the leading explanation seems to have rou=
ghly=C2=A0these features:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Alameda Research, a crypto hedge fund=
 that is affiliated with FTX (both founded by Sam Bankman-Fried, both run o=
ut of the same group apartment in the Bahamas, etc.), had huge leveraged po=
sitions on FTX and elsewhere.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">FTX =
loaned Alameda lots of money to keep those positions going.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">As Alameda=E2=80=99s problems got worse, FTX gave=
 it more money, rather than shutting it down and liquidating its positions.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">By delaying, the exchange caused =
a much bigger problem, ultimately bringing down FTX and Alameda and vaporiz=
ing customer money.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. I am not sure that expla=
nation is exactly right. But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t it look like LM=
E? Doesn=E2=80=99t it look like =E2=80=9CI had the keys to the castle at th=
at point in time, and it would=E2=80=99ve been a very bad day=E2=80=9D? Doe=
sn=E2=80=99t it look like an exchange bending its rules to extend more cred=
it to a well-connected insider whale? And then the whale taking everyone el=
se down with it? Alameda was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>getting blown out as so=
on as its positions moved against it; Alameda was accumulating more and mor=
e risk until the whole exchange came down.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all a bit speculative, but I think two=
 reasonable lessons to take from=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s blowup might be somethi=
ng like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At the margin, you should be=C2=A0<em=
>less=C2=A0</em>persuaded=C2=A0by FTX=E2=80=99s proposal to have exchanges =
hold customer collateral directly: This is a reminder that exchanges can=E2=
=80=99t always be trusted with customer money, and distributing that risk t=
o many brokers might be better.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At=
 the margin, you should be=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>persuaded by FTX=E2=80=
=99s proposal to have margining be automatic and instantaneous: This is a r=
eminder that, when exchanges have discretion about extending credit to big =
well-connected whales, they sometimes make disastrous decisions.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here are two Bloomberg News articles lo=
oking back at FTX=E2=80=99s proposal. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/29719674.276531/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
