d Sam Bankman-Fried can scrape together, offset by $9 billion of FTX custom=
er liabilities. So some things on that balance sheet =E2=80=94 in particula=
r a stake in Robinhood Markets Inc. =E2=80=94 seem to belong to Bankman-Fri=
ed entities that are not part of the FTX bankruptcy, but are being thrown i=
n here to raise cash. I am going to say =E2=80=9CFTX=E2=80=9D in the text b=
ut I mean more like =E2=80=9Cthe FTX/Alameda/SBF consolidated group.=E2=80=
=9D One thing that I do not understand is the status of FTX.us, FTX=E2=80=
=99s US entity, which is separate from FTX but also seems to have shut with=
drawals.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] That is: $554 million of the FTT token tha=
t provides fee discounts on FTX itself, $2,187 million of the SRM token of =
FTX=E2=80=99s Project Serum decentralized exchange, and $616 million of the=
 MAPS token of another FTX project. I think some other assets on that balan=
ce sheet might also fall into this category, though in smaller sizes. And $=
982 million of Solana=E2=80=99s SOL token are also a risky proposition if y=
ou think that the success of the Solana blockchain depends in part on its t=
ies to FTX.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] Also it is silly to be too precise here, b=
ut the balance sheet we all saw =E2=80=94 because the Financial Times publi=
shed it =E2=80=94 is from last Thursday. I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what =
time it took its prices from, but I conservatively estimate that FTT and MA=
PS are down about 40% since then, with SRM down about 14%. That puts the va=
lue of this stash at about $2.56 billion, down almost $800 million from las=
t Thursday, almost enough to wipe out the net equity on that balance sheet.=
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-5" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[5] That number is, like, there is about $1 bi=
llion of liquid assets on the balance sheet, and about $9 billion owed to c=
ustomers, so if you pay out the $1 billion and get $8 billion more of cash =
from an investor, you can pay off the customers. And then the investors who=
 put in the $8 billion get to keep the $9 billion of semi-liquid and illiqu=
id assets, making this =E2=80=94 on Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s math =E2=80=94 =
an attractive deal for those investors. That=E2=80=99s the theory.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
